Red Wine Quality Exploration

Holly Moore

30 August, 2020

The dataset used in this exploration contains 1,599 red wines. It has 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wines. A minimum of three wine experts rated the quality of each wine, and they provided a rating between 0 and 10 (0 being very bad, and 10 excellent). We will explore which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines.

Looking at the acidity levels

Fixed acidity ranges from 4.6 to 15.9. It has a reasonably normal distribution, skewed slightly right, with a median 7.9 and mean of 8.32.

Volatile acidity ranges from .12 to 1.58. The distribution is also fairly normal, would be considered bimodal with peaks at 0.4 and 0.6, and slightly skewed right. The median and the mean are almost the same (median 0.52, mean 0.5278).

Citric acid ranges from 0 to 1, with most observations falling at zero, and another peak at 0.49. There is minimal citric acid in red wine.

1.1.2 Residual Sugar Level

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.900   1.900   2.200   2.539   2.600  15.500

Residual sugar levels range from 0.9 to 15.5, with a median 2.2 and a mean of 2.539. The distribution is heavily skewed right, with most observations falling under 3. Since we have a very long tail, the bottom graph is transformed using a log scale 10 on the x-axis to get a better look.

1.1.3 Chloride level

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.01200 0.07000 0.07900 0.08747 0.09000 0.61100

The Chloride levels range from 0.012 to 0.611 and are heavily skewed right, with 75% of the observations at or below 0.09. Since we have a long tail, the bottom graph (scale x log 10), zooms in so we can see what is going on. On the transformed plot (excluding observations above 0.20), the distribution appears normal.

Free sulfur dioxide has a wide range from 1 to 72, but 75% of observations fall at 21 and below. The median is 14, and the median is 15.87. The distribution is heavily skewed right like many of the other variables we have looked at. Due to the long tail, logscale was used on the x-axis, allowing us to see a sharp peak 6. After seeing the peak at 6, I ran the table command so we could see how many of each number we were dealing with. There are 138 observations with number 6.

1.1.5 Total Sulfur Dioxide Levels

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    6.00   22.00   38.00   46.47   62.00  289.00

Total sulfur dioxide has an even wider range, from 6 to 289, but 75% of observations fall at 62 and below. The median is 38, and the median is 46.47. The distribution is heavily skewed right. We used logscale to transform the x-axis, giving us a better look at the data. The transformed data has a normal distribution peaking between 40-50.

1.1.6 Density

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9901  0.9956  0.9968  0.9967  0.9978  1.0037

The density of wine has a minimal variance range, from 0.9901 to 1.0037 (difference of only 0.0136). The minimal variance is not surprising since all wine has the consistency of water, which is 1g/cm3. The distribution is normal with the median and the mean being almost the same (median 0.9967 & mean 0.9968).

1.1.7 pH Levels

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.740   3.210   3.310   3.311   3.400   4.010

The pH levels also have a small variance range, from 2.74 to 4.01 (difference of 1.27). The distribution is normal, almost symmetrical, with the median and the mean being almost the same (median 3.310 & mean 3.311).

1.1.8 Sulphate Levels

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.3300  0.5500  0.6200  0.6581  0.7300  2.0000

The sulphate levels range from 0.33 to 2.0, but 75% of all observations fall at 0.73 and below. The median is 0.62, and mean 0.6581. The distribution is right-skewed with some outliners on the far left.

1.1.9 Alcohol Level

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.40    9.50   10.20   10.42   11.10   14.90

The alcohol level ranges from 8.4 to 14.9. The mean and the median are almost the same (median 10.2, mean 10.42). The distribution is right-skewed with the peak at 9.5. The highest rating of 14.9 looks like an outliner.

The quality rating scale goes from 0 to 10, with 10 being the best. However, in this dataset, our ratings go from 3 to 8 (8 being the best). The distribution is normal, peaking between five & six. Most of the observations are between 5 & 7.

2 Univariate Analysis

2.0.1 What is the structure of your dataset?

This dataset contains 1,599 observations and has twelve variables (11 of which are chemical properties of the wines). The variables are: fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality.

2.0.2 What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main item of interest is wine quality. We are exploring the chemical properties to determine which ones influence the quality of red wines.

2.0.3 What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Since we are interested in red wine quality, we want to locate the variables that affect quality. Right now, I am interested in the variables that correlate with quality.

2.0.4 Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No.

2.0.5 Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The dataset came nice and tidy. While making the initial variable plots, adjusting the bin size was about all that needed to be done. And four of the variables (residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide) had long tails. In order to zoom in and get a better picture of the distribution, I used scale_x_log10 on the x-axis to transform the data.

3 Bivariate Plots Section

Above, we have two different correlation matrix plots. They make it easy to see the strength of the relationships between the variables.

In the first matrix plot, the higher the correlation, the bigger the font used for the correlation strength.
For fun, I threw in the second matrix plot. In this matrix, the strength of the relationship is represented by color, the darker the shade (either red or purple), the stronger the relationship.

Correlations with Quality
Although some of these correlations are relatively weak, they are still listed here. Variables with the strongest correlation to quality are:
0.48 alcohol
-0.39 volatile acidity
0.25 sulphates
0.23 citric.acid

As for the relationships between the other supporting variables, there are quite a few interesting correlations we can see (both positive and negative).

Negative correlations
-0.68 pH vs.fixed.acidity
-0.55 volatile.acidity vs.citric.acid
-0.54 pH vs.citric.acid
-0.50 alcohol vs.density

Positive correlations
0.67 fixed.acidity vs.citric.acid
0.67 fixed.acidity vs.density
0.67 total.sulfur.dioxide vs.free.sulfure.dioxide
0.37 sulphates vs.chlorides
0.36 residual.sugar vs.density

I am surprised to see only a few variables correlate to wine quality, I expected more. However, there are still plenty of correlations to explore.

Now we will plot some of the correlations!

Here we have the two variables with the highest correlation with quality and then added quality to them. Citric acid levels do not seem to matter as much as we can see high levels throughout the spread of citric acid.

8 Reflection

In this dataset, we examined 1,599 different red wines. The goal was to determine which variables contributed to the quality of the wine. I started by spending time looking at each variable individually.

Then I checked the correlation between the variables. It was surprising to find that the highest correlation was only -0.68. I had expected alcohol level to have a higher correlation, but then I suppose that would make it too easy to produce quality wine. If the alcohol level were the key, wine makers could9 increase the alcohol level and be done with it, but nothing is ever that simple. After that, then I spent some time plotting the correlations of interest. I had hoped there would be more variables correlate with quality, but I used what we had. The most surprising plot for me was the correlation between quality and citric acid. It had a very weak correlation, and citric acid levels are very low in wine in general. I did not expect to see much of anything when I plotted these two variables. However, instead, we saw a very definite increase in quality as the citric acid level increased.

In the multivariate plots, we were able to get a look at three variables together. My favorite plot was putting alcohol, volatile acidity, and quality together. I had examined these variables separately, but bringing them together painted a nice picture of red wine quality (higher alcohol levels, along with lower volatile acidity = better red wine quality).

I selected the smallest dataset to use for this project. Now I wonder how this would have gone had I selected the dataset with a larger sample size. I would have like to see the quality ratings on a larger sample size. I am curious if we would still see 95% of the wines falling between a quality rating of 5-7 or getting more variety. Had there been more wines with the highest quality rating, perhaps it would have been easier to determine which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines.

This was my first time using Rstudio, and the options seem endless! I loved exploring different things and seeing all the different types of plots and analyses available in R.
